To determine if an integer `n` is a power of three without using loops or recursion, you can take advantage of the binary representation of `n`. If `n` is a power of three, then the binary representation should contain a contiguous 10x1 sub-sequence starting from the most significant bit (MSB). This pattern arises because every time 3 raises to a power increases by a factor of three, the number of 1s in its binary representation increases by one.

Here's a Java method to check if a number is a power of three based on this property:

```java
public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Calculate the number of 1s in the binary representation of n
    int count = 0;
    int current = n;
    while (current > 0) {
        if ((current & 1) == 1) {
            count++;
        }
        current >>= 1;
    }

    // If the number of 1s is not a multiple of 3 or n itself isn't a power of three (base case with one 1-bit), return false.
    return count > 0 && (count % 3) == 0 || (n == 1);
}

// Optimized version without counting bits
public static boolean isPowerOfThreeOptimized(int n) {
    return n > 0 && ((1U << (32 - Integer.numberOfLeadingZeros(n) % 3)) == (1L << 32 - Integer.numberOfLeadingZeros(n)));
}

// This method uses a constant time approach by checking the least significant bits of the number
public static boolean isPowerOfThreeConstantTime(int n) {
    return (n > 0 && (n % 1000L) == (3L << (32 - Integer.logBase2(3L).intValue() * LogBase2AndBitShiftConstant.LOG3_BASE.getValue())));

